{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489699","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489699"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:26:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:26:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"720"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"720","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/720"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.47,0.16,0.16,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"720"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108848"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"720","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/720"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"720"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91212"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"517"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4046"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9067"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2579"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33627"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43809"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44760"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108848","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108848"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 57-year-old man presents with a one week history of vomiting on a background of six months of anorexia and weight loss. His medical history includes alcoholic liver disease, chronic pancreatitis and appendicectomy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination he appears pale and cachectic. His blood pressure is 90/60 mmHg, pulse 120/min and temperature 37.0C. His abdomen is distended and soft. The liver span is 10 cm. A succussion splash can be elicited.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chronic pancreatitis","Carcinoma of the pancreas","Small bowel obstruction","Liver failure","Metastatic liver disease"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA succussion splash is the audible sloshing of fluid in a distended stomach. This sign can be elicited by the examiner putting a hand on each flank and then firmly shaking the abdomen from one side to the other. The sound reflects the presence of gas and fluid in the distended (and usually obstructed) stomach. As a clinical sign, it has a low sensitivity but high specificity for gastric outlet obstruction (GOO). The most common cause of GOO is malignancy, specifically \u003Cstrong\u003Epancreatic adenocarcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E. It is estimated that about 20% of these patients will develop gastric outlet obstruction. In this case, the diagnosis of pancreatic cancer is supported by the background of weight loss, anorexia and chronic pancreatitis - a strong risk factor. The patient may not necessarily be jaundiced on presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn exacerbation of chronic pancreatitis is an important diagnosis to consider, as it can occasionally cause GOO. However, this patient has red flags for malignancy and should be treated as such until proven otherwise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESmall bowel obstruction (SBO), secondary to malignancy or adhesions, would present with vomiting and dehydration. A gastric volvulus could cause GOO, but a SBO would not. Both alcoholic liver disease and metastatic liver disease would cause hepatomegaly and ascites, but not gastric outlet obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Malignancy is the most common cause of gastric outlet obstruction"],"references":["Koop AH, Palmer WC, Stancampiano FF. Gastric outlet obstruction: A red flag, potentially manageable. Cleve Clin J Med. 2019;86(5):345-353. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31066665/","McGrath C, Tsang A, Nithianandan H, et al. Malignant Gastric Outlet Obstruction from Pancreatic Cancer. Case Rep Gastroenterol. 2017;11(3):511-515. Available at; https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29033771/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91212"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"720"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91212","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91212"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-13T19:23:41+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-13T19:23:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"720"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108848"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","